    <fr:title text="Binary classification">Binary classification</fr:title>
  </fr:frontmatter>
  <fr:mainmatter><html:ul><html:li>A <html:em>classifier</html:em> is a function mapping from <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {X}]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{-1, 1\}  ]]></fr:tex>.</html:li>
  <html:li>The nearest neighbor classifier maps some <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {x}]]></fr:tex> to the label of its nearest neighbor.</html:li>
  <html:li>The <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[k]]></fr:tex>-nearest neighbor classifier takes the majority of the <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[k]]></fr:tex>-nearest neighbors</html:li>
  <html:ol><html:li>What is the effect of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[k]]></fr:tex>?</html:li>
    <html:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[k]]></fr:tex> affects smoothness and therefore the tradeoff between overfitting and underfitting.</html:li></html:ol></html:ul><html:p>To introduce the algorithms that follow, we must first introduce the bayes-optimal classifier. To do so, they formulate this as a problem of representing the joint distribution of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(X,Y)]]></fr:tex>, where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex> is the class label and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> is the observation. They propose two decompositions:</html:p><html:ol><html:li>Class posterior <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P_{Y|x}]]></fr:tex> and data marginal <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P_X]]></fr:tex></html:li>
  <html:li>Class conditional <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P_{X|y}]]></fr:tex> and class prior <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P_Y]]></fr:tex></html:li></html:ol>
